Here's what I found:

### Hardcoded Value in `app.js`

**Port number on lines 18-19** — The server port `3000` is hardcoded directly in the source. This should be pulled from an environment variable so it can be configured per environment (dev, staging, production, container platforms like Heroku/Railway that assign dynamic ports).

**Current:**
```javascript
app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log('Server running on port 3000');
});
```

**Recommended fix:**
```javascript
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`);
});
```

### Other Observations

| Item | Assessment |
|------|-----------|
| **`alice@example.com` / `bob@example.com`** (lines 13-14) | Mock/demo data — acceptable as-is, but if this were a real app, user data would come from a database, not be inline. |
| **`.env.test` credentials** | Contains DB URLs, AWS keys, Stripe keys, etc. — these are already stored as environment variables (good practice), though they appear to be canary/test values. Just make sure `.env.test` is in `.gitignore` and never committed with real secrets. |

